83–1343":"1283–1343","1228–Male":"1228–Afdød","1229–Female":"1229–Afdød","about 1280":"omkring 1280","1253":"1253","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","about 1318":"omkring 1318","1259":"1259","1343":"1343","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1229":"1229","Pershore, Worcestershire, England":"Pershore, Worcestershire, England"},"nl":{"1253–about 1318":"1253–circa 1318","1253–1318":"1253–1318","1250–1338":"1250–1338","1283–1343":"1283–1343","1228–Male":"1228–Overleden","1229–Female":"1229–Overleden","about 1280":"circa 1280","1253":"1253","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","about 1318":"circa 1318","1259":"1259","1343":"1343","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1229":"1229","Pershore, Worcestershire, England":"Pershore, Worcestershire, England"},"en":{"1253–about 1318":"1253–about 1318","1253–1318":"1253–1318","1250–1338":"1250–1338","1283–1343":"1283–1343","1228–Male":"1228–Deceased","1229–Female":"1229–Deceased","about 1280":"about 1280","1253":"1253","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","about 1318":"about 1318","1259":"1259","1343":"1343","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1229":"1229","Pershore, Worcestershire, England":"Pershore, Worcestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walter","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (of Norman origin), German, Dutch, Polish, Swedish, and Danish: from a personal name composed of the ancient Germanic elements <i>wald</i> ‘rule’ + <i>heri</i>, <i>hari</i> ‘army’. This personal name was introduced into England both in the reign of Edward the Confessor and by the Normans (in the forms <i>Walt(i)er</i>, <i>Waut(i)er</i>). After the Norman Conquest it soon became one of the most popular personal names in Britain. Compare   Walther  .","Germanized or Americanized form of Czech, Slovak, Croatian, and Slovenian <b>Valter</b> and Czech <b>Valtr</b>: from the personal name <i>Valter</i>, <i>Valtr</i>, of ancient Germanic origin (see 1 above)."],"variants":[{"name":"Walthers","meanings":["German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Walther</i> (see   Walter  )."]},{"name":"McQuate","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uait</b> ‘son of <i>Uat</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Irish form   McQuaid  ."]},{"name":"Waltke","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Jurgen, Wilhelmina.","German: from a pet form of any of the ancient Germanic personal names formed with Old High German <i>waltan</i> ‘to rule’ as the first element, as in   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McWaters","meanings":["Scottish and northern Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b>, a patronymic from a Gaelicized form of the personal name   Walter  , with excrescent English <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Wahler","meanings":["German:","from the personal name <i>Wol(d)er</i>, Low German form of   Walter  .","habitational name for someone from any of various places called Wahl, Wahle, or Wahlen."]},{"name":"McWalter","meanings":["Irish and Scottish: from Gaelic <b>Mac Uaitéir</b> ‘son of   Walter  ’."]},{"name":"Walters","meanings":["English: variant of   Walter  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>.","German: patronymic from   Walter  ."]},{"name":"McQuaid","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Colum, Nuala.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Uaid</b> ‘son of <i>Uad</i>’, Gaelic form of the personal name <i>Wat</i>, a short form of   Walter  . Compare the Scottish form   McQuate  ."]},{"name":"Walther","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Erwin, Wolfgang, Otto, Gerhard, Gunter, Heinz, Klaus, Konrad, Bernd, Bernhard.","German, Dutch, Swedish, and Danish: variant of   Walter  ."]},{"name":"Lauter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Erwin, Kurt, Sigismund, Wolf.","German: topographic name and habitational name, from a common stream name meaning ‘clear’, from Middle High German <i>hlutra</i>, or from any of the places called Lauter or Lauta (Saxony). This surname is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine) and some other European countries.","Germanized or Americanized form of Slovenian <b>Lavtar</b> or its Croatized and rare Slovenian variant <b>Lautar</b>: from a dialect variant of the personal name <i>Valter</i> (see   Walter  )."]}]},{"name":"Elizabeth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual spelling of   Elisabeth   in English. It is recorded in the medieval period, but was made popular by being borne by  Queen Elizabeth I  of England (  1533–1603 ). In the 20th century it again became extremely fashionable, partly because it was the name of  Elizabeth Bowes-Lyon  (  1900–2002 ), who in  1936  became Queen Elizabeth as the wife of King George VI, and after his death in  1952  achieved great public affection as Queen Mother for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":6,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":37,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":62,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Walter was born in 1253, in Pershore, Worcestershire, England, her father, Thomas Walter, was 26 and her mother, Dama Walter, was 24. She married Sir John Vampage II about 1280, in Pershore, Worcestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died about 1318, in her hometown, at the age of 66."},"et":{"1253–about 1318":"1253–umbes 1318","1253–1318":"1253–1318","1250–1338":"1250–1338","1283–1343":"1283–1343","1228–Male":"1228–Surnud","1229–Female":"1229–Surnud","about 1280":"umbes 1280","1253":"1253","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","about 1318":"umbes 1318","1259":"1259","1343":"1343","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1229":"1229","Pershore, Worcestershire, England":"Pershore, Worcestershire, England"},"fi":{"1253–about 1318":"1253–noin 1318","1253–1318":"1253–1318","1250–1338":"1250–1338","1283–1343":"1283–1343","1228–Male":"1228–Kuollut","1229–Female":"1229–Kuollut","about 1280":"noin 1280","1253":"1253","1283":"1283","1250":"1250","1290":"1290","1228":"1228","1338":"1338","1315":"1315","about 1318":"noin 1318","1259":"1259","1343":"1343","1318":"1318","1317":"1317","1229":"1229","Pershore, Worcestershire, England":"Pershore, Worcestershire, England"},"fr":{"1253–about 1318